04719nam a22006375i 9780226592886DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018019707  a9780226592886  a(DE-B1597)524013  a(OCoLC)1125192855  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aF869.S39bJ3586 2019 4aF869.S39bO33 2019 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a979.4/6104956223  aLB 486102rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90563:9831 aOda, Meredith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Gateway to the Pacific :bJapanese Americans and the Remaking of San Francisco /cMeredith Oda. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b18 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Studies of Urban America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Japan and Japanese Americans in the Pacific Metropolis through World War II -- tChapter Two. Orienting the Gateway to the Pacific: Reconsidering Japan and Reshaping Civic Identity -- tChapter Three. Redeveloping Citizens: Planning a New Japanesetown -- tChapter Four. Pacific Crossings: Japan, Hawai‘i, and the Redefinition of Japanesetown -- tChapter Five. Intermediaries with Japan: The Work of Professional Japanese Americans in the Gateway -- tChapter Six. Local Struggles: Japanese American and African American Protest and Cooperation after 1960 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the decades following World War II, municipal leaders and ordinary citizens embraced San Francisco’s identity as the “Gateway to the Pacific,” using it to reimagine and rebuild the city. The city became a cosmopolitan center on account of its newfound celebration of its Japanese and other Asian American residents, its economy linked with Asia, and its favorable location for transpacific partnerships. The most conspicuous testament to San Francisco’s postwar transpacific connections is the Japanese Cultural and Trade Center in the city’s redeveloped Japanese-American enclave. Focusing on the development of the Center, Meredith Oda shows how this multilayered story was embedded within a larger story of the changing institutions and ideas that were shaping the city. During these formative decades, Oda argues, San Francisco’s relations with and ideas about Japan were being forged within the intimate, local sites of civic and community life. This shift took many forms, including changes in city leadership, new municipal institutions, and especially transformations in the built environment. Newly friendly relations between Japan and the United States also meant that Japanese Americans found fresh, if highly constrained, job and community prospects just as the city’s African Americans struggled against rising barriers. San Francisco’s story is an inherently local one, but it also a broader story of a city collectively, if not cooperatively, reimagining its place in a global economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEthnic neighborhoodszCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanese AmericanszCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrban renewalzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAsian Americans.  aCold War.  aJapanese Americans.  aSan Francisco.  aTranspacific.  abuilt environment.  aredevelopment.  aurban history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226592886423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226592886/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  Uni